Viewed Hi Everyone,

At the moment, I am struggling with multiple problems. The first problem is that I am battling a health condition that prevents me from working as usual. Unfortunately, it has developed into a chronic issue and I need to find a way to deal with this. I have been in and out with doctors, alas, with little result. I don't want you to worry, it's not going to kill me, but at the moment I am unwell.

The second problem is that we are missing sponsors again. This problem recurs each year in January, as many brands focus their marketing resources between Thanksgiving and New Year. So we have too many sponsors in December, but come January, and their budget is exhausted. This year the drop is more pronounced than in previous years. I don't know why, but the weak dollar isn't helping. 

I also want to make some changes to the channel content to cover some new content and improve the presentation, but it will take time to pull this off. 

Oh, and I want to write a new book, too...

For all these reasons, it is foreseeable that in the next weeks videos will appear less regularly than in the past years. I am reasonably confident that with time we will reach a new level of stability, but until then, I hope for your understanding. 

I have so many interesting things to tell you about: An update on Kessler's syndrome, the problem with biofuels, and a physicist who says we can send messages between branches in the many worlds theory...

Stay tuned,

Sabine

title:
Viewed Hi community,
"The AI Hippocampus:
How Far are We From Human Memory?" is an interesting perspective to compare the diff of AI mem to human mem. 

quote: "the survey delineates three primary memory frameworks. 

Implicit memory refers to the knowledge embedded within the internal parameters of pre-trained transformers, encompassing their capacity for memorization, associative retrieval, and contextual reasoning. Recent work has explored methods to interpret, manipulate, and reconfigure this latent memory. 

Explicit memory involves external storage and retrieval components designed to augment model outputs with dynamic, queryable knowledge representations‚Äîsuch as textual corpora, dense vectors, and graph-based structures‚Äîthereby enabling scalable and updatable interaction with information sources. 

Agentic memory introduces persistent, temporally extended memory structures within autonomous agents, facilitating long-term planning, self-consistency, and collaborative behavior in multi-agent systems, with relevance to embodied and interactive AI. 

Extending beyond text, the survey examines the integration of memory within multi-modal settings, where coherence across vision, language, audio, and action modalities is essential.

A.  OpenTinker
"We introduce OpenTinker, an infrastructure for reinforcement learning (RL) of large language model (LLM) agents built around a separation of concerns across algorithm design, execution, and agent‚Äìenvironment interaction. Rather than relying on monolithic, end-to-end RL pipelines, OpenTinker decomposes agentic learning systems into lightweight, composable components with clearly defined abstraction boundaries. "
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.07376

B.   Active Evaluation of General Agents: Problem Definition and Comparison of Baseline Algorithms
"As intelligent agents become more generally-capable, i.e., able to master a wide variety of tasks, the complexity and cost of properly evaluating them rises significantly. Tasks that assess specific capabilities of the agents can be correlated and stochastic, requiring many samples for accurate comparisons, leading to added costs. In this paper, we propose a formal definition and a conceptual framework for active evaluation of agents across multiple tasks, which assesses the performance of ranking algorithms as a function of number of evaluation data samples."
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.07651

C.   VirtualEnv: A Platform for Embodied AI Research
"As large language models (LLMs) continue to improve in reasoning and decision-making, there is a growing need for realistic and interactive environments where their abilities can be rigorously evaluated. We present VirtualEnv, a next-generation simulation platform built on Unreal Engine 5 that enables fine-grained benchmarking of LLMs in embodied and interactive scenarios. VirtualEnv supports rich agent‚Äìenvironment interactions, including object manipulation, navigation, and adaptive multi-agent collaboration, as well as game-inspired mechanics like escape rooms and procedurally generated environments"

Viewed This new image shows two huge spiral galaxies that swung past each other millions of years ago, and their gravity is now yanking and twisting their beautiful spiral arms. Astronomers combined two kinds of vision to make this picture: infrared light from the James Webb Space Telescope, which highlights warm dust and places where new stars are forming, and X-ray light from the Chandra X-ray Observatory, which shows extremely hot gas and intense high‚Äëenergy activity.
‚Äã

Even though the close encounter itself was brief in cosmic terms, the consequences will last for billions of years as the galaxies slowly lose energy, spiral closer together, and eventually merge into one larger galaxy. In other words, this snapshot is just one frame in a very long gravitational dance that will completely reshape both galaxies over time.

Credit: NASA/CXC/SAO; Infrared: NASA/ESA/CSA/STScI/Webb; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/L. Frattare

Viewed On a more positive note. I continue to see those of you asking about updates re: my non-40K creative writing project. Ive so far spent about 2 years working on it, and I thought I was going to have it close to an edited format I could deliver around the end of this year, this didnt happen because after some harsh personal reflection, I ripped up the structure as it was, because I could feel it wasnt working and fundamentally altered some key components of characters and worldbuilding. 

So now its back to being 'on the way' still, the positive is that I now feel clearer than ever in my mind about some of the story arcs and motivations now. 
I'll be working on this in the coming months - and likely finally commissioning some artwork. I plan to bring this to the channel maybe in spring 2026. 

How will that go? Who knows, but thats life. Feedback so far has been good, which is heartening and either way I feel very motivated and positive to put this into a format I can finally release.

Viewed Hi elvira, I really love your work.
I have a suggestion for a video that I think you might find interesting:
you could explore the relationship betwen early Putin and Berlusconi. At the time Silvio was a pioneer of the art of taking control of media in a relatively free country, Vlad was in the process of creating his personal myth and a couple of years away from starting his own takeover of Russian media.
From Italian eyes, how Putin did this looked a lot like a more aggressive version of what we had experienced. We saw Putin morph from a grey KGB like presence to a well crafted TV character. It all looked very familiar.
I think there are many interesting aspects to the way the 2 interacted and possibly influenced each other. 
There are also some hilarious ones I KNOW will inspire you in your writing: you might look up the story of "il lettone di Putin" (Putin's big bed). It's an episode that involves villas with fake volcanos, parties, extreme luxury, crime, corruption and, like most episodes involving Berlusconi, several hookers and the negative effects a poorly handled mid life crisis can have on the institutions of a republic.
Not sure how much you can find about this in English, but I'll be happy to help you with that, if you need it.
I hope you'll consider it someday.

Please keep making your wonderful content with such passionate insight, your work is necessary.

Viewed Hi community,
interesting new technical report on all the new methods deployed for the Qwen 3 Vision Language Model. 

It natively supports interleaved contexts of up to 256K tokens, seamlessly integrating text, images, and video. The model family includes both dense (2B/4B/8B/32B) and mixture-of-experts (30B-A3B/235B-A22B) variants to accommodate diverse latency‚Äìquality trade-offs. 

Qwen3-VL delivers three core pillars: 

(i) markedly stronger pure-text understanding, surpassing comparable text-only backbones in several cases;

(ii) robust long-context comprehension with a native 256K-token window for both text and interleaved multimodal inputs, enabling faithful retention, retrieval, and cross-referencing across long documents and videos; and 

(iii) advanced multimodal reasoning across single-image, multi-image, and video tasks, demonstrating leading performance on comprehensive evaluations such as MMMU and visual-math benchmarks (e.g., Math-Vista and MathVision). 

They introduce three key upgrades: 
----------------------------------------------------------
(i) an enhanced interleaved-MRoPE for stronger spatial‚Äìtemporal modeling across images and video; 
(ii) DeepStack integration, which effectively leverages multi-level ViT features to tighten vision‚Äìlanguage alignment; and 
(iii) text-based time alignment for video, evolving from T-RoPE to explicit textual timestamp alignment for more precise temporal grounding.

Link
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.21631

Viewed Hi community,
New Ai research (yesterday) that if you show a short video to an AI, the AI will understand the spatio-temporal logic of the video, and if you ask for the next logic step in the time evolution (like how to tie a Windsor knot), the AI will generate a short video for you - showing you the next step. 

Holy smoke, I had no idea we can already do this! 
now you ask for the technical details: The input question is tokenized and fed into the VLM (Vision Language Model)  alongside high-level ViT (Vision Transformer) visual features from the input video. We task the VLM with performing instruction-grounded reasoning to generate a textual caption describing the predicted next event, which serves as the semantic guide for the VDM (Video Diffusion Model) . 

To ensure visual consistency, the VDM is conditioned on both the generated caption and low-level visual cues, which are extracted by tokenizing n sampled input frames using a VAE (Variational Autoencoder); these tokens are then concatenated into the VDM‚Äôs conditioning latent space. This enables fine-grained visual correspondence while generating novel scenes. All subscribers of my channel are familiar with those technical terms, since we went through all of those model tech already with multiple videos. But this combination is new: "Video-Next-Event Prediction (VNEP)" .

The core of VANS is a newly proposed Joint-GRPO that orchestrates the VLM and VDM to function as a unit. Driven by a shared reward on their respective output, it optimizes the VLM to produce captions that are both accurate and friendly to visualize, while guiding the VDM to generate videos that are faithful to these captions and the input visual context.

Recommend this new Ai paper for interesting insights
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.16669
"Video-as-Answer: Predict and Generate Next Video Event with Joint-GRPO"
By Junhao Cheng, Liang Hou, Xin Tao, Jing Liao
City University of Hong Kong and Kling Team, Kuaishou Technology.

Viewed Hi community, *** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W6VJn7XU090  ***
want to build your own RAG system with your own files and code and PDFs and your own docs? Now Google offers this for free (just indexing is 15 cent per 1 million token). Google does the heavy lifting for you. No coding for you.

Similar to Notebook LM, where you could upload your files and PDF to have an audio summary or some learning flashcards, Google now offers "FILE SEARCH" - which is de facto building a complete vector space with vector representations of your texts and words, on basis of tokens = RAG. 

And then you can query this vector database with your questions, so you do not need to pay for external vector stores. Plus you can choose the LLM you want for the reasoning complexity (or switch to newer LLMs when available), when your RAG external data streams are brought back and are added to your query. No coding. Just upload your files and Google builds it for you - automatically. Done. 

I have a first real world test and it performed well. See my new video

new Ai paper about "Advances of LLM for MEDICINE". 
The authors argue, that in practice, medical practitioners often find traditional solutions inadequate when faced with the vast amount of medical literature and complex diagnostic case records. Can current AI augment medical support? 

The authors: 
" First, AI technology is still immature. Despite the numerous
outstanding features of LLMs, AI technology remains in
continuous development and cannot fully replace doctors
in applying professional knowledge and skills to address
patients‚Äô problems. Second, there is the issue of data bias:
the quality and accuracy of training data determine the
performance of LLMs, and if the data used for training is
biased, the capabilities of the resulting LLM will likewise
be affected. Finally, there are privacy and security concerns.
Medical data is private patient information, and if it is leaked
or misused, the consequences can be serious. Therefore, pri-
vacy and security must be prioritized in LLM applications."

Viewed Hi community,
You know I love Physics, so when I discovered a new paper " Towards a PHYSICS Foundation Model" I had to read it. Main insights:

A.  Introduces the General Physics Transformer (GPhyT), a transformer-based neural architecture designed to serve as a foundational model for simulating diverse physical systems governed by partial differential equations (PDEs). The architecture hybridizes a spatiotemporal transformer (for differentiation) with a numerical integrator (Forward Euler), promoting efficiency and stability.

B.  Multi-Physics Learning: A single transformer can model disparate systems (e.g., incompressible flows, shock waves, thermal convection) without domain-specific features.

C.  GPhyT as a step toward a universal physics simulator, potentially accelerating fields like fluid dynamics and materials science.

D.  No real-world experimental data, images, or videos were used; all inputs are numerical simulation outputs (e.g., 2D grids of fields like velocity, pressure, density, temperature). Each sample is a time-series of 2D snapshots.

The General Physics Transformer (GPhyT) operates without being provided the underlying governing equations, including the Navier-Stokes equations. The model is trained solely on simulation data (numerical outputs from solvers that implement those equations for specific datasets, such as shear flow and obstacle flow). 

It infers the temporal evolution of physical fields (e.g., velocity, pressure) from contextual input prompts consisting of prior state snapshots, augmented with numerically computed first-order derivatives (dx, dy, dt) via central differences on the input data. This allows GPhyT to approximate the dynamics in a data-driven manner, producing predictions that mimic the behavior of numerical simulations without symbolic knowledge of the equations.

TOWARDS A PHYSICS FOUNDATION MODEL
School of Data Science, University of Virginia &
Chemical Process Engineering, RWTH Aachen University
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.13805

INTEL published a new paper on a lossless compression of Neural Network Components: Weights, Checkpoints, and K/V Caches in Low-Precision Formats (FP8).

They extend the ZipNN approach to lower-precision floating-point formats, specifically FP8 and FP4, which are gaining popularity for efficient inference. Our evaluation shows compression ratios up to 62% for BF16 and 83% for FP8.

INTEL investigates the compressibility of key-value (K/V) cache tensors used in large language models (LLMs),
finding that they, too, exhibit compressible patterns, enabling memory savings during deployment. Enabling effective entropy encoding, thereby offering runtime memory savings without modifying inference logic.
